porting jobs.","index":"00267","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3) Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the\nclosure, which will also impact the local economy.","index":"00268","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4) As of January 27, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already\nmore than 250 inmates over capacity. ","index":"00269","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00270","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin.","index":"00271","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nhas been signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00272","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDiljeet </b><b><a name=\"_Toc34813145\">Brar</a></b><b>�(Burrows):</b> I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly of Manitoba.","index":"00273","speaker":"Diljeet Brar"},{"html":"����� These are the reasons for this petition:","index":"00274","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Many\nfarmers, specifically cattle ranchers, will be negatively impacted by the\nchanges to leased Crown land announced by the provincial government on\nSeptember 27, 2019. ","index":"00275","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Farmers\npreviously had the ability to strategically plan out the way in which they\nutilized their leased Crown land. ","index":"00276","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nannouncement reduced leaseholds by 35&nbsp;years to 15 years, and these changes\nwill create great uncertainty, having the potential to impact an entire farm's\noperation and even existence. ","index":"00277","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nuncertainty will take away the incentive for farmers to safely invest in their\nCrown land leases. ","index":"00278","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\npotential of losing these leases without the afforded time to plan ahead will\ncreate additional stress for the current farming generation and the ones to\nfollow. ","index":"00279","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\npetition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows: ","index":"00280","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the Minister of Agriculture to reconsider the changes to Crown land leases\nand instead create an agreeable strategy that satisfies all parties,\nspecifically ranchers; ","index":"00281","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the Minister of Agriculture to recognize the value of agriculture in the\nprovince of Manitoba and the value Crown land holds to farmers in sustaining\ntheir livelihood; ","index":"00282","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the Minister of Agriculture and all honourable members to understand the\nimportant role farmers play in the Manitoba economy, and to allow them to take\npart in discussions that directly impact their livelihood. ","index":"00283","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nhas been signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00284","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou. ","index":"00285","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Ian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc34813147\">Bushie</a></b><b>�(Keewatinook):</b>\nMadam Speaker, I wish to present the following petition to the Legislative\nAssembly.","index":"00286","speaker":"Ian Bushie"},{"html":"����� To the\nLegislative Assembly of Manitoba:","index":"00287","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nbackground to this petition is as follows:","index":"00288","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) The provincial government plans to close the Dauphin Correctional\nCentre, DCC, in May 2020.","index":"00289","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2) The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing\nthe community with good family-supporting jobs.","index":"00290","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3) Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the\nclosure, which will also impact the local economy.","index":"00291","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4) As of January 27, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already\nmore than 250 inmates over capacity. ","index":"00292","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00293","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plans to build a new\ncorrectional and healing centre with an expanding courthouse in Dauphin.","index":"00294","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Signed\nby Patricia Start, Brittany Wellborton <i>[phonetic]</i>, Laurie Austin <i>[phonetic]</i>.","index":"00295","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Tom </b><b><a name=\"_Toc34813148\">Lindsey</a></b><b>�(Flin\nFlon):</b> I wish to present the following petition for the Legislative\nAssembly of Manitoba.","index":"00296","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� The\nbackground to this petition is as follows:","index":"00297","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) The provincial government plans to close the Dauphin\nCorrectional Centre, DCC, in May 2020.","index":"00298","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2) The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing\nthe community with good family-supporting jobs.","index":"00299","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3) Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the\nclosure, which will also impact the local economy.","index":"00300","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4) As of January 27, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already more\nthan 250 inmates over capacity. ","index":"00301","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00302","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin.� ","index":"00303","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And this petition, Madam Speaker, has been signed by Norma\nSutherland, Chantel Plett, Jim Fleming and many other Manitobans. ","index":"00304","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Matt </b><b><a name=\"_Toc34813149\">Wiebe</a></b><b>�(Concordia):</b> I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly. ","index":"00305","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� And the background to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00306","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1)\nThe provincial government plans to close the Dauphin Correctional Centre, DCC,\nin May 2020. ","index":"00307","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2) The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing\nthe community with good, family-supporting jobs.","index":"00308","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3) Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the closure,\nwhich also impact the local economy.","index":"00309","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4) As of January 27th, 2020 Manitoba's justice system was already\nmore than 250 inmates overcapacity.� ","index":"00310","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows: ","index":"00311","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin. ","index":"00312","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And\nthis petition, Madam Speaker, is signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00313","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Jon </b><b><a name=\"_Toc34813151\">Gerrard</a></b><b>�(River Heights):</b> Madam Speaker, I wish to present the following\npetition to the Legislative Assembly. ","index":"00314","speaker":"Jon Gerrard"},{"html":"����� The background to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00315","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1)\nManitoba elders and seniors have built this province and should receive a high\nlevel of support, having earned the right to be treated with due respect,\ndignity, understanding and compassion as a funda�mental human right. ","index":"00316","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2) Seniors who reside in personal-care homes have more diverse and\ncomplex physical and brain health issues today than those who were in similar\nhomes even just five years ago, yet the staffing formula, or minimal personnel\nrequirement, is over 20&nbsp;years old. ","index":"00317","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The issue of the changes to, and more complex nature of, care is\nbeing exacerbated by the provincial government policy of discharging people out\nof hospitals more quickly, leaving many residents still in need of a high level\nof care. ","index":"00318","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4) Manitoba does not have enough health-care aides and nurses\nspecifically trained to care for seniors with high and complex levels of\nphysical and mental issues such as those with dementia, coupled with multiple\nchronic conditions. ","index":"00319","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (5) The added complexity of care with such residents is putting\nadditional stress on doctors and family members, as it may take six to eight\nweeks for a doctor to see a resident in a personal-care home. ","index":"00320","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (6) Unfortunately, the lack of quality care received by many\nresidents is not unique, causing one person to say that: It was easier to watch\nmy dad die in the personal-care home than to watch him live in the\npersonal-care home.","index":"00321","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (7) Staff are so overworked that they are forced to tell senior\nelders and residents in need: Go in your diaper; I can't help you. You will get\nfood eventually. ","index":"00322","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (8) Relatives are also being told that residents in care homes\nshould not ever expect to walk again after hip or knee replacement surgery\nbecause care homes are not set up for rehabilitation. ","index":"00323","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (9) The provincial government has allowed personal-care homes to\nserve food that is warmed from frozen instead of being freshly cooked,\ndepriving seniors the taste of good food, which is one of the few real\npleasures that would be�they would be able to enjoy at this time of life. ","index":"00324","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (10) Although residents enter personal-care homes to have the best\npossible quality of life in their last few days, weeks, months or years,\nrelatives repeatedly hear the words: He came here to die; and: She came here to\ndie. ","index":"00325","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Relatives are regularly angry, frustrated, disap�pointed and\nshocked at the care their loved ones now received in Manitoba's personal-care\nhomes. ","index":"00326","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (12) Administrators in personal-care homes respond to complaints by\nstating they need more, better-trained staff. ","index":"00327","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows: ","index":"00328","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the provincial government to increase training and staffing\nrequirements for personal-care homes in Manitoba to ensure residents receive\nhigh-quality, nutritious food as well as compassionate care. ","index":"00329","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Signed\nby Wendy Bloomfield, Art Bloomfield, Sarah MacAulay <i>[phonetic]</i> and many\nothers. ","index":"00330","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><span lang=\"FR-CA\">*</span></b><span lang=\"FR-CA\"> (14:40) </span>","index":"00331","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><span lang=\"FR-CA\">Ms. Malaya </span></b><b><a name=\"_Toc34813153\"><span lang=\"FR-CA\">Marcelino</span></a></b><b><span lang=\"FR-CA\">�</span>(Notre Dame):</b> I wish to present the\nfollowing petition to the Legislative Assembly.","index":"00332","speaker":"Malaya Marcelino"},{"html":"����� To the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba:","index":"00333","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The background to this petition is as follows:","index":"00334","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) The provi